<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<!--
		Ad-hoc-signing variant of MatronMac.Debug.entitlements, used by
		the integration harness scripts (which sign with
		`CODE_SIGN_IDENTITY=-`). Identical to the regular Debug
		entitlements MINUS `keychain-access-groups`: that entitlement
		needs a provisioning profile to validate against an AppID,
		which ad-hoc signing doesn't provide, so xcodebuild rejects
		the build with "MatronMac requires a provisioning profile" if
		the group is present here.

		The harness opts into this file via
		`CODE_SIGN_ENTITLEMENTS=$ROOT/MatronMac/App/MatronMac.Debug.AdHoc.entitlements`
		on the xcodebuild command line, overriding the per-config
		default (`MatronMac.Debug.entitlements` which DOES include the
		keychain group, used by Xcode-Run dev builds with proper
		signing — DEVELOPMENT_TEAM=4LJ7WRRRFD per project.yml).
		Without this split, properly-signed Debug builds from Xcode
		lost their Keychain access, and the recovery-key flow
		surfaced "Couldn't auto-save your recovery key" on every
		first sign-in. See `MatronMac.entitlements` (Release) for the
		canonical full set.

		Keychain writes from `RecoveryKeyManager.generateAndPersist`
		will fail with `errSecMissingEntitlement (-34018)` against a
		build using this file at runtime — but the view-model handles
		that path via `PersistenceError.keychainWriteFailedButKeyAvailable`
		and shows the recovery key to the user even when the local
		write fails, so the harness scenarios still drive the SAS
		round trip to completion.
	-->
	<key>com.apple.security.network.client</key>
	<true/>
	<key>com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-only</key>
	<true/>
</dict>
</plist>
